<!-- ===============================================
     SECTION 2: WHY THIS AREA
================================================ -->
<section style="background:var(--color-base, #f2efe9); padding:80px 24px;">
  <div style="max-width:800px; margin:0 auto;">
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.15em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#c4912a; margin-bottom:1rem;">Local Expertise</p>
    <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif); font-size:clamp(1.8rem, 3.5vw, 2.8rem); font-weight:300; line-height:1.2; color:#1c1917; margin-bottom:1.75rem;">The inner south-west corridor's family heartland.</h2>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      Sherwood sits roughly eight kilometres south-west of the CBD, bordered by Graceville to the east, Chelmer to the north, Corinda to the west, and Rocklea to the south. It is an established family suburb with a strong identity: the Sherwood Arboretum provides a large and genuinely leafy park at the suburb's centre, and the Oxley Creek corridor runs through the surrounding area, giving Sherwood a green space amenity that separates it from comparable inner suburbs at similar distances from the CBD. The housing stock is a mix of character Queenslanders and post-war homes on generous blocks, and the suburb's tree-lined streets and unhurried pace make it a consistent draw for families looking to settle in the inner south-west.
    </p>
<!-- APPRAISAL FORM -->
