<!-- END APPRAISAL FORM -->
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      Sherwood's value framework is anchored to its neighbours. Buyers comparing Chelmer and Graceville set the price ceiling for the corridor, and Sherwood's relative accessibility on that scale is its primary draw for families who want the inner south-west lifestyle but have found Chelmer and Graceville out of reach. Secondary value drivers are meaningful in their own right: the Sherwood Arboretum and Oxley Creek green space are genuine premiums for families with children, Sherwood train station provides direct CBD access that keeps the suburb competitive for professional buyers, and character home integrity continues to attract buyers seeking original Queenslanders or well-maintained post-war homes on larger blocks. Relative to Graceville in particular, Sherwood offers an accessible entry without sacrificing the corridor character that defines the inner south-west.
    </p>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      Selling in Sherwood requires understanding the overflow buyer dynamic that shapes this market. The buyers who matter most in Sherwood are often buyers who have already been watching Chelmer and Graceville, who understand the corridor well, and who redirect to Sherwood when supply or price pushes them out. Reaching that buyer means positioning not just against Corinda to the west, but directly against Graceville and Chelmer to the north and east, and making a clear case for why Sherwood represents the next-best opportunity on the same corridor. A campaign that ignores this dynamic and markets Sherwood in isolation will underperform one that actively addresses the overflow narrative.
    </p>
    <div style="display:flex; gap:1.5rem; flex-wrap:wrap;">
      <div style="flex:1; min-width:200px; background:#fff; padding:1.75rem; border-left:3px solid #c4912a;">
